metadata.name: Pulsar #114
metadata.description:
When exploring new possibilities for a new work, I stumbled across an article on Pulsar map. Created by astronomer Frank Drake and Carl Sagan, this map serves as a galactic address of our solar system for any extra-terrestrial civilization to find using pulsars as signposts. Though chances of any kind of life form intercepting the map are slim, I'm still fascinated both by the possibility of another planetary civilization finding the map (and by extension our Earth), and the thought of using pulsar -- the remaining corpse of ancient massive star -- as universal signposts and landmarks to map the Earth position for any kind of possible civilization. To me there's something so poetic about this; it made me thinks of how small are we, the Humans, compared to those rotating pulsars that we use as mere landmarks to our location...let alone the whole universe. We are just floating stardust after all.

In this piece I use Lissajous curve array with randomized variable to position the stars and generate spline as 'star trails'. The Lissajous array is interpolated with Perlin noise array to make it less smooth and looks more random.



----------
Control:
Press [s] to capture a screenshot of the current viewport.
Press [t] to toggle the star trails (default: enabled).



Made with Cables.gl

XALTED 2022

metadata.name: the centre cannot hold #135
metadata.description:
The spiral is one of the earliest symbols used by humans, found in cave paintings and petroglyphs, and is thought by some researchers to have been inspired by shamanic rituals and hallucinogenic experiences. 

The spiral is found in our mathematics via the golden ratio, and in our aesthetics via the Fibonacci Spiral, aka the Golden Spiral. Spirals are found throughout the natural world, from the shape of our galaxy, to hurricane storms in our atmosphere, to seashells in the oceans.   

Spirals are also used to conceptualize entropy, spiraling out of control, the downward spiral from order into chaos. Each of these works represents this form of spiral, with varying degrees of chaos versus order, a formerly-cohesive group throwing off parts of itself due to overwhelming centrifugal force.   
--  
Uses p5js (LGPL-2.1). Color palettes are inspired by the paintings of Mondrian, Rafael, Van Gogh, Munch, O'Keefe, and Magritte.

metadata.name: primordial soup #118
metadata.description:
1024 kinematic automata that imitate living organisms, leaving behind a trace of paint before going extinct. Blotches of paint are deposited by these nodes that attract and repulse each other according to rules based on their color and size.

Short description of features:
- mood: the palette
- tone: the noisiness
- flow: the number of neighbors affecting each node
- brow: the brush size
- delirium: brush modifier
- distancing: kinetic rule modifier

Each feature is equally likely - rarity is in the eye of the beholder.

@balidani

metadata.name: walkinthepark #136
metadata.description:
Mazes are almost entierly context-free. The mazes of `walkinthepark` have no entrance or exit. Not all of them are solvable. Any resemblance to reality is pure coincidence.

All features are distributed equally:
- weave - The internal pattern of sub-mazes.
- density - The density of the sub-mazes.
- color - Yep.
- aim - How big the biggest sub-maze can get.
- bars - How connected sub-mazes are.
- stroke - The randomness of lines.
- skew - How much some sub-mazes are rotated.
- grain - How many sub-mazes are rotated.

@balidani, Dec 2021

metadata.name: Hatch Field 001 #240
metadata.description:
Genesis p5js drawing on fx(hash). Experimenting with translating recent work in done in Grasshopper exploring hatch patterns to p5.js. By Andrew Kudless / Matsys @matsysdesign
There are four feature groups:
- Base Hue: Red, Orange, Yellow, Spring Green, Green, Ocean Green, Cyan, Sky Blue, Blue, Purple, Magenta, and Crimson. Each has the same random chance of being the base color (12%).
- Hue Range: Narrow (14%), Wide (51%), and Infinite(34%)
- Lineweight: Thin (75%), Medium (10%), Thick (10%), Extra Thick (5%)
-Fray: Loose (90%), Tight (10%)

metadata.name: Scattered Architectures #91
metadata.description:
“Scattered Architectures” is a generative experiment about the illusion of space created by flat surfaces that share edges.

This project drives inspiration from some beautiful drawings by Diane Scott: https://www.instagram.com/dianescottstudio/

Made by Leonardo Solaas

metadata.name: Hypericum #194
metadata.description:
This system translates color into movement. A swarm of drawing particles, like virtual pencils, are guided by the color values of the pixels in an input image. The formulas performing the conversion put into play many parameters. The space of possibilities of the system is enormous, the variety of drawings endless. 256 is just a small arbitrary sample. 

This work can be seen as a playful reflection on the concept of “style”, which is so essential to our ideas about art and (human) artists. This short program can paint the same image on infinitely many “styles” – each of them reducible to a simple combination of mathematical parameters. 

The input image is a photo of a yellow hypericum flower I took during a holiday in the Argentinean Patagonia, near Bariloche, in 2016.

Better on landscape format (optimal ratio is 3:2) > on your computer, [open live]
Press [s] to download capture.

Made by Leonardo Solaas
TW > @solaas
IG > @leonardo_solaas
WWW > solaas.com.ar

metadata.name: éclats #84
metadata.description:
Started as a simple exploration of circle packing, this generative piece became "éclats".
I play around colors, contrasts and details to create some kind of lights. Some composition and palette might remind you some fireworks, some cities viewed from the sky, some flower fields or... Whatever comes to your mind.

Note: depending on the features, the generation might take a bit of time.
